metadata.name: Tangentum #170
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Punktwelt #516
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ’s’ to save a png. Press ’4’ to export a high resolution png. Press ’8’ to export a very high resolution png. Press ’e’ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: Endeavor #5
metadata.description:
Endeavor is a generative system structured to create abstract mountains.

When I look at the outputs, I am reminded of the things I would like to achieve. I would be curious to know what comes to your mind when you ask yourself, "What is my goal? What do I intend to do?"

Controls:

'p' - Play an animation that draws the mountain layer by layer
'1' - Default, textured image
'2' - No border
'3' - Flat, non-textured image
'4' - Flat with no border

Each of the 128 editions chooses one of five forms, all of which explore variety in layout, shading, and color composition.

25% of the royalties for each edition will pass to the original minter.

Each output is generated from code written in p5js.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Dithered Nostalgia #97
metadata.description:
Have you ever struck by a sudden surge of nostalgia?
Making you stop everything you did at that moment,
Trying hard to remember the memory behind it, and failed to do so?

Each of these lands hold a nostalgia unlocked,
Like how good nostalgia are, it’s dithered and full of holes.
Holes that can be filled with your own memories and interpretations.

• • •

The second collaboration of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. This time using MEK.txt’s landscape pixelart series and its distinctive dithering textures, brilliantly translated into code by IceRain to pixel-perfect iterations.

Dithered Nostalgia is a step up from MEK.txt & IceRain’s first project (Bento Boxes), trying to make more sophisticated, more detailed and challenging things based on something they passionate about; landscape.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: Glitchy Masks #36
metadata.description:
A big thank you to Aleksandra from https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Aleksandra for their assistance with the code!

In this project, I explored the concept of randomness and was pleasantly surprised by the results. After a few iterations, masks began to emerge. I added a mirroring effect to enhance the visual and added eyes for added realism. The end result is a series of intriguing masks, created through the use of randomness and artistic experimentation.

To save your canvas, simply press S.

For more information and to stay up to date with my work, follow me on Twitter at @lomzart or visit my portfolio website at lomz.net. Thank you for your interest!

metadata.name: The Woodcarver's apprentice #33
metadata.description:
A mix of aesthetics from the Ukiyo-e and Shin-hanga woodblock movements, with modern elements.  

ukiyo-e (浮世絵) = "pictures of the floating world", which peaked in the late 19th century. 
shin-hanga (新版画) = "new prints", from roughly the 1920-1950s. 

Some comparisons between the prints of the Japanese masters and gen-art: 

* The number of prints. Based on how well a piece was received, the publisher could decide to produce more copies, usually in batches of 200. Compare this to limiting the edition size on fx(hash). The initial prints would have sharp lines and accurately coloured areas. Very popular prints with thousands of impressions would slowly degrade the blocks, leaving final prints with worn-out linework and colours that weren't true to originals.  

* Woodblock prints were actually a collab between the artist, the wood carver, and the printer. In many cases only the artist and publisher were recognized on the final prints. It was usually the publisher who owned the woodblock, not the artist. Often the artist was considered a worker, contracted at the request of the publisher or patrons funding the project. Compare this to the NFT space, where ownership is carved onto the blockchain, and artists have freedom to create whatever they wish. 

* Copyminters.... Similar to the NFT world, fake publishers sprang up from time to time, who would reproduce famous prints. Enji Takamizawa was one such counterfeiter, who was able to skilfully produce woodblocks replicating originals down to the wood grain! 

* While fine-quality woodblock prints from the Edo era command huge auction prices today, they were in reality affordable art for the regular people of their time. NFTs are similar in this light, where we can enjoy pieces at home rather than say, visiting galleries or museums of unattainable art. 



Additional querystring params (use when viewing in a separate window) 

* fullsize=true (33 megapixel output) 
* colourcorrect=false 
* grain=false 
* border=false 



Licenses included in source. Relying on: 

* PIXIJS for drawing 
* JSTS for geometry functions 
* chromajs for colour functions 
* noise and gaussian helpers from p5js

metadata.name: Asterium #145
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: Imperium #84
metadata.description:
Imperium is a study of shapes and colors, and how a very small set of shapes and colors, when given equally simple rules, can create a great variety of patterns that may bring meaning to the viewer.

metadata.name: Infinite Scaling System #118
metadata.description:
This generative system has a beginning, but no ending. It scales infinitely in different directions as unlimited shapes are added. Special care was taken to avoid memory overflows, impossibly big numbers, and poor performance. 

Rendered using P5.JS

metadata.name: Levitation #104
metadata.description:
Abstract structures floating in space. 

——————

Levitation continues my exploration of Suprematism and Geometric Abstraction. It contains my developments and ideas for the past half a year.
Starting as mostly inspired by Kleine Welten (Small Worlds) series by Wassily Kandinsky, the collection evolved more into Suprematic compositions.

——————

To change the size of an image, open it in live view and add ‘&size=[size (6200 max.)]’ to the end of the URL.

Controls:
[Arrow Up / Down] — increase / decrease animation speed.
[R] — skip the animation.
[C] — switch between clean and grainy versions.
[S] — save the image.

Created using p5.js and GLSL.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

——————

hrunz. — Nov. 2022.

metadata.name: fx(mash) #125
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #189
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”
